column52: Provision of Engagement Activity & Volunteer Services in Darlington
column53:
The Northern Inclusion Consortium (NIC), is an established partnership of four of the North East's largest charities - DISC, Groundwork, Changing Lives and Mental Health Concern. See www.niconsortium.org for more information.
The NIC is inviting interested parties to tender for the provision of engagement activity & volunteer services in Darlington as part of the Step Forward Tees Valley Programme.
Working with a broader set of delivery partners we are delivering the Big Lottery Fund / European Social Fund funded Building Better Opportunities Programme in Tees Valley through the Step Forward Tees Valley Programme. The programme aims to improve employability for the most disadvantaged and provide help to those with multiple and complex needs using a case management model.  For more information about the programme please follow this link www.sfteesvalley.co.uk.
We now wish to buy in additional provision to encourage suitable people to access and engage with the programme and to develop volunteering opportunities in the Darlington area.
The Northern Inclusion Consortium is inviting interested parties to tender for the supply and delivery of a service across the Darlington area to:
- Increase the access and engagement of participants onto the SFTV programme
- Build the capacity of organisations to provide volunteering opportunities
- Provide participants on the programme with volunteering opportunities
- Provide ongoing support to participants and organisations during the volunteering placement
- Work with other partners to increase the skill, knowledge base and employability prospects of participants on the programme.
Download the Invitation For Tender for full information on this provision and how to submit a tender.

column52: 7637 Interpretation for Divers on England's Protected Wreck Sites: SM U-8 Virtual Trail
column53:
Historic England is seeking to receive submissions for an interpretation project relating to the protected submarine U-8 for the non-diving public. It is envisaged that the project will create a virtual trail that is accessible by all. The Project will help develop our understanding of the site and in turn aid its future management.
      
      The proposed scheme should bring the site to life for the non-diving public. It should be designed to be hosted on a responsive website that is designed for mobile use. The scheme should be hosted by the contractor in the first instance with the possibility for it to be hosted by Historic England in the longer term. It should be user friendly and include a variety of media to guide people around the site.
      
      Designation details of the SM U-8 Protected Wreck Site may be found on the relevant List Entry here:  https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1430265

Additional information: Suppliers interested in submitting a bid for this contract should express an interest via the Historic England procurement system InTend.

column52: PAN1656 - Waste Composition Analysis
column53:
Leicester City council through the operation of a 25year PFI contract with Biffa Leicester, collect, treat and dispose of all municipal waste generated by Leicester residents.  This includes treatment of the refuse collected through the 'Ball Mill' which is used to extract the organic fraction, metals, and RDF leaving an inert fraction for final disposal in landfill.  The organic fraction is then treated in our Anaerobic Digester.  
To establish the materials contained in our waste streams and to provide high resolution information Leicester City Council intends to undertake a Waste Composition Analysis (WCA) of 4 key waste streams:
	Household recycling (orange bag or bin)
	Household refuse (black bin)
	Inert stream (waste destine for landfill after processing by the Ball Mill)
	Floc or RDF (baled waste fraction sent as RDF)
The information gathered on the materials contained within our waste streams, will allow better understanding of the wastes generated in Leicester, the potential to increase recycling rates, and help guide future strategies.  The information will also help our understanding of our current capture rates and shape our future strategies for encouraging waste minimisation and tailored communication campaigns.
column58: Sewage, refuse, cleaning and environmental services

column52: Mountbatten Building - Primary Chilled Water System Remedial Works (Planon Project 5844) - AWARD
column53:
The University of Southampton is seeking to appoint a Contractor to deliver Primary Chilled Water System Remedial Works within the Mountbatten Building located on the Highfield Campus as outlined below:
      The original installation comprised two chillers, one being an absorption chiller (CH-21-101) and the second a screw chiller (CH-21-102), in 2012 a third screw chiller (CH-21-103) was installed as part of an earlier, but not entirely successful, remedial works project. The chiller plant has been plagued with poor operational performance which has led the University to obtain capital fund to replace/amend the primary cooling system.
      The scope of works associated with the replacement of the primary cooling system includes the following plant and equipment:
      a. Absorption Chiller (CH-21-101) with integral controls
      b. Screw chiller (CH-21-102) with integral controls
      c. Screw chiller (CH-21-103) with integral controls
      d. Cooling Towers (CTR-25-401 & 402)
      e. Primary Chilled Water Pumps (PMP-21-101, 102 & 103)
      f. Condenser Water Pumps PMP-25-201 & 202.
      g. Pressurisation Unit (MSC-21-101)
      h. Associated trend BEMS controls and condenser water pipework, chilled water pipework up to and including the primary flow and     return headers and any other pipework etc.
      The project shall be to remove all redundant plant and equipment, to install as necessary new plant and equipment and carry out all necessary improvements to retained existing plant and equipment together with all associated builderswork etc. to create a complete new primary chilled water system that delivers chilled water to the low loss header in compliance with this specification and a subsequent associated Service Level Agreement (SLA).
      The Contractor shall be at liberty to reuse and incorporate into the amended installation any or all of the above existing components except for the Trend BEMS installation. The reason for not reusing the existing BEMS being that this will continue to control other existing plant outside of the new SLA.
      The Contractor shall be responsible for ensuring that any reused existing components are suitably repaired/modified/maintained to ensure that they can operate in a suitably reliable and efficient way to meet the conditions of the SLA for operation and maintenance of the primary chilled water system including but not limited to meeting Guaranteed Performance requirements.
      The tender returns will be assessed under a whole life-cycle cost analysis over a 10-year study period. The analysis will include the impact of proposed chiller efficiency at full and part load operation, associated plant (new and retained), maintenance and utility costs. A whole life cycle spreadsheet will be included within the tender documentation for the Contractor to complete. 
      A performance specification and supporting drawings will be provided which outlines a suggested design only with key performance criteria, the tenderers will be encouraged...

column52: ESPH SB Deliver of Waste, Recycling and Street Cleansing Services - Soft Market Test
column53:
Rother District Council, on behalf of the East Sussex Joint Waste Partnership (comprising Eastbourne and Hastings Borough Councils and Rother and Wealden District Councils), wishes to understand the current operational issues and working practices in the Waste and Recycling industry to inform the specification, payment mechanisms and risk sharing arrangements prior to going to tender.  The current contract is due to expire in June 2019 and in preparation for the impending tender process we have prepared the enclosed soft market test.

At present the current Waste, Recycling and Street Cleansing Contract provides a service to circa 200,000 households with the Eastbourne Borough Council area receiving weekly residual waste collections and Hastings Borough Council, Rother District Council and Wealden District Council receiving alternate weekly collections (AWC) with all districts receiving AWC kerbside recycling.

Included in this service is a fortnightly, opt-in Garden Waste Service.  The service also includes the delivery of a bulky waste service, residential clinical waste collections and street cleansing.  Hastings and Eastbourne are primarily urban in nature, and Rother and Wealden urban/rural.  The districts also have significant beach areas important for tourism.  

The Council wishes to use to engage with the market and undertake this market engagement exercise to establish the current issues and opportunities facing the market in the delivery of these services and use the results of this exercise to help it shape the future contract.

To clarify, this is a soft market test and not a call for competition or tender opportunity.

Completed questionnaires should be email to procurement@rother.gov.uk by 28th July 2017.
column178: East Sussex Procurement Hub, c/o Wealden District Council

column52: University of Sunderland - AM Package 8 - CNC Lathe, Mill & Router
column53:
AMAP (Automotive and manufacturing advanced practice) form a key part of the Faculty of Engineering and Advanced Manufacturing at the University of Sunderland.  
      
      The University actively seeks to work with industry and that creates an exciting dynamic. Our vision for AMAP is to inform, inspire and innovate in Advanced Manufacturing, which we will achieve by being an innovative, accessible, and outward facing provider of support for industry. This will be based upon the application of research and knowledge of Advanced Manufacturing regionally, nationally and internationally - adding unique value and excellence to differentiate and enhance the student experience, the Faculty of Engineering & Advanced Manufacturing and the University.
      
      The University of Sunderland has the research capability supported by AMAP, and AMAP also have their network of industrial contacts. AMAP is trusted and respected by suppliers because of its neutral position. Our practice understands industry and we appreciate the challenge of the competitiveness within the supply chain. We are here to support businesses, large and small, by sharing contacts and best practice, providing training and up skilling of the workforce, plus carrying out research and then sharing the findings.
      
      Recognised regionally, nationally and internationally, adding unique value and excellence to differentiate and enhance the student experience, AMAP seeks to be innovative, accessible and an outward facing provider of support for industry.  Based upon the application of research and knowledge of advanced manufacturing.
      
      Summer 2017 will see a significant investment from University of Sunderland into Advanced Manufacturing.  Work will be conducted at two key sites (St Peters Campus - David Goldman Building and The Industry Centre) and your attention is drawn to Appendix D - Floor Plans - which confirms the current floor layouts of these areas and associated equipment requirements.
      
      As such, the University of Sunderland seeks to appoint an innovative supplier/service provider who can provide a comprehensive and compliant response to the requirements outlined within this ITT for Advanced Manufacturing Equipment defined as a Manual CNC Lathe and associated equipment.

column52: Expression of Interest - The supply of gas and electric in void properties.
column53:
The London Borough of Hounslow is looking for a company that can assist us with the issues we face, which are to clear the debts on our gas and electric meters which are left from previous tenants.

The contractor/supplier will need to provide tag codes to reset the meter, which we would require within 24 hours of us reporting the void to them.

We require the contractor/supplier to supply cards and keys to us, so we can supply them, once we receive a void ready for when tag code is received.

We would also require, the company to assist when there are faulty meters.  They will need  to get an engineer to site in a timely manner to resolve the problems, to ensure that the void turnaround  time is not delayed.

The change of supply cannot, delay the letting of a property, as this would affect our turnaround time.

We would require the supplier/company, to ensure that the tenants have freedom to change their supplier, once the property is re-let.  

We cannot have a tenant tied into a contract with whoever supplies the contract we cannot authorise a decision like this on the new tenants behalf.'          If you are interested in this opportunity please login to the London tenders portal  https://procontract.due-north.com/Advert?advertId=8e529d86-ce5c-e711-80e3-005056b64545  and express your interest.       Increase effectiveness of data acquisition and reporting to allow the University to  evaluate student attainment in relation to bursary payments

column52: District Heating Network & CHP Design Services
column53:
The existing District Heating Network at our Lancaster campus is at the end of its economic life. Regular leaks impose an ongoing financial on the university (circa ?30k pa). Complete failure of the system is a growing threat which if realised will have significant impact on operational activities.
      
      To investigate the choices to resolve this issue, Arup were appointed to produce an options appraisal. From these studies it was concluded there are two viable options:
       
      1. Break up the DH Network and introduce distributed gas boilers, or 
      2. Replace the DH Network and introduce a Combined Heat & Power (CHP) plant.
      
      With comparable capital costs, preference was given to option 2 based on the lifecycle benefits, a much more attractive payback period and eligibility for external funding.
      
      The UoC Estates & Property Team now have the need to appoint an M&E Consultant to develop a detailed design of the scheme. This design will form the basis of the Contractor tender documentation. Developing a comprehensive design in a timely fashion will be key to the success of this scheme. A targeted project completion date of late September 2018 ensures timescales are tight across the whole programme.

column52: Sentinel 1 Backscatter Data Provision Service
column53:
This project will investigate several technical issues regarding the production of standardised backscatter data derived from Sentinel 1 data.  It will then provide a service to generate and deliver backscatter data from Sentinel 1 imagery.  In order to address the different aspects of the work that are required, the following specification is broken down into a number of modules.  Each will need to be planned and costed separately so that decisions can be taken regarding priorities for the work within available resources.  The modules are:
1.	To carry out a short test by processing one or two Sentinel 1 scenes using 4 different combinations of settings.  The outputs of this test will be presented to stakeholders so that a decision can be taken as to how to modify the processing chain described in Annex B.
2.	To provide a service to generate and deliver imagery from the Sentinel 1 satellite processed into a backscatter product for the UK to the modified specification decided upon following the initial test phase.  This will enable multiple uses of that data and prevent the duplication of that processing.  Once created, that data will be made available for JNCC to ingest via an API into the Defra Collaboration Platform within a fully automated process.  All Sentinel 1A and 1B imagery over the UK from 1st January 2017 to 31st March 2018 will be included in the contract.  This module will also provide a troubleshooting element to ensure that support is available should anything go wrong with technical aspects of the data delivery.
3.	To carry out a detailed technical comparison between the modified version of the processing chain described in Annex B and other proposed standards such as from the CEOS Analysis Ready Data for Land (CARD4L) and the Satellite Applications Catapult.  This will assess the differences between the proposed standards and the likely implications of those differences for users.
4.	To provide a service to generate and deliver imagery from the Sentinel 1 satellite processed into a backscatter product for South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands.  This will utilise the same approach as the UK service, but will need refining in order to address issues such as data mode, positional accuracy and coordinate systems to use.
5.	To carry out an assessment of the size of the task and the likely technical difficulties that would be faced in producing Sentinel 1 backscatter for the UK Overseas Territories.  Production of data for these areas is not part of this contract, but the assessment will advise on the best method, to include specifications of projections to be used and to estimate the costs of producing that data.

Additional information: If you are unable to access the tender documents, please follow the link below to review and download documents including the ITT

http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/page-7435

column52: Communication Support Services
column53:
The Contracting Authorities:- 
	NHS Brighton and Hove Clinical Commissioning Group (B&H CCG)
	Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust (BSUH)
	Sussex Community NHS Foundation Trust (SCT)
	Sussex Partnership NHS Foundation Trust (SPFT)
Are considering the re-procurement of Communication Support Services and wish to conduct market engagement before deciding their route to commission the services.
The Contracting Authorities are seeking views and comments from suppliers on the services required  through the use of a Request for Information (RFI) document which contains further information about the requirement and a questionnaire.
To access and download the RFI document please follow the web links at the bottom of this advert.  
Please return the form by Tuesday 2nd May 2017 according to the instructions on page one of the RFI document.
This process does not constitute the start of a formal procurement.
Brighton and Hove CCG (BHCCG), Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust (BSUHT), and Sussex Community NHS Foundation Trust (SCFT), have worked as a collaborative to commission local communication support services for the local populations accessing services overseen or provided by these organisations; the current contract has run from 2014 and will end March 2018. In addition, for ongoing work, Sussex Partnership NHS Foundation Trust (SPFT) will be a partner in the recommission. 

The organisations agree that there is added value in developing locally responsive services, that are able to respond to the needs of the demographic of the patients accessing primary care in Brighton and Hove, and the services of BSUH, SCFT and SPFT across the geographic areas they serve.
The Authorities envisage recommissioning communication support services will be for a three year contract, from April 2018 to March 2021 and the Authorities will have an option to extend by a period of up to a further 24 months

Additional information: Additional information has been added to update suppliers following feedback received by the Contracting Authorities to their earlier engagement (Request for Information) and an invitation to suppliers to attend a bidder event on 12th July 2017.

column52: Tilting Gravity Casting Cell
column53:
Further to the successful development of the AMCC 1 programme in the Brunel Centre for Advanced Solidification Technology (BCAST) at Brunel University London (BRUNEL), the second phase development (AMCC 2) is now being established to expand this unique national facility for light metal research in processing and characterisation for fundamental research and industrial applications. Together with the EPSRC Future Liquid Metal Engineering Hub, and AMCC1, AMCC 2 will provide high performance light alloys, resource efficient manufacturing technologies and component innovations with advanced materials characterisation facilities to meet the long- and mid-term needs of UK industry. 
The initiative is funded by the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE), and supported by a number of industrial partners. Funding for equipment at the AMCC 2 is available in the period up to 31st March 2017 to assist in establishing the new facilities at Brunel University London in Uxbridge. The equipment will be purchased by BRUNEL. All equipment must be accepted and staff trained on the Uxbridge site by the end of March 2017 at the latest.
An advanced tilting gravity casting system for aluminium alloys is required to be set up. The system must be versatile enough to be configured for research and development

column52: Contract for a Pressure Filtration Cleanliness Analyser
column53:
Further to the successful development of the AMCC 1 programme in the Brunel Centre for Advanced Solidification Technology (BCAST) at Brunel University London (BRUNEL), the second phase development (AMCC 2) is now being established to expand this unique national facility for light metal research in processing and characterisation for fundamental research and industrial applications. Together with the EPSRC Future Liquid Metal Engineering Hub, and AMCC1, AMCC 2 will provide high performance light alloys, resource efficient manufacturing technologies and component innovations with advanced materials characterisation facilities to meet the long- and mid-term needs of UK industry. 
The initiative is funded by the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE), and supported by a number of industrial partners. Funding for equipment at the AMCC 2 is available in the period up to 31st March 2017 to assist in establishing the new facilities at Brunel University London in Uxbridge. A pressure filtration cleanliness analyser is required for consistent assessment of Aluminium and Magnesium alloy melts for inclusion content such as refractory contamination and naturally occurring oxide particles and films. Based on the assessment characteristics, capability of the equipment to assess the impact of melt quality on fluidity is also required together with some capability of predicting defect formation during and after mould filling for real castings. The equipment should be a standard fully developed product with capabilities mentioned above, without having the need for us to customise for our needs.

column52: Agreement for 'Always on' Digital Marketing Recruitment Plan
column53:
LJMU wishes to engage a Supplier to work in partnership with us to deliver a step-change in our digital marketing to prospective students. 
To date, our approach has been to run digital campaigns to drive traffic to the website, increase social engagement, signpost prospects to recruitment events and to raise awareness of vacancies available over the Clearing period. This has helped to create spikes of interest. 

In recognition of the fact that prospective students expect to find the information they need across their media consumption channels of choice at a time that suits them, our approach moving forward is to invest in 'always-on' digital marketing activity aimed at reaching more prospects and maximising opportunities to receive as many high-quality applications as possible. 

Creating a year-round 'push and pull' digital channel mix, providing a combination of awareness, nurturing and direction throughout the consideration journey will be a key differentiator for LJMU in the marketplace.

We are therefore looking to appoint an Agency with proven, first-class expertise in digital marketing to work in partnership with us to deliver a digital marketing strategy that is underpinned by robust analytics and insights to allow us to deliver increasingly targeted marketing communications across a range of platforms

Additional information: Companies who have interest in this opportunity should visit the Intend link attached on this advert and view the documents, to ascertain if this is a suitable project.

If you have any queries arising from the opportunity , then these should be placed via the Intend system , not via email

column52: 12400 - Demolition & Associated Works of 1-17 Markford Walk and 159-169 Melbourne Avenue, Hockley, Birmingham, B19 - WITHDRAWN
column53:
Acivico Building Consultancy invites organisations to be considered to receive tender documentation for the DEMOLITION AND ASSOCIATED WORKS INCLUDING SITE CLEARANCE OF 2no THREE STOREY DETACHED TOWN HOUSES, NEWTWON, BIRMINGHAM, B19
      
      Contract Number 12400
      
      It is considered that the three storey detached 'Wimpey No Fines' constructed properties are no longer suitable and the site is earmarked for redevelopment, therefore identifies the need for safe demolition and site clearance.
      
      The site must be well secured by use of appropriate fencing during and at the end of the contract. Contractors wishing to tender for this contract must have 3 years of audited accounts showing a minimum annual average turnover of 500k.
      
      The contractor must provide suitably trained workforce and experience/knowledge of works required to be undertaken. The contractor will be responsible for providing their own power, water and welfare to undertake this work.
      
      A Public/Product liability insurance of 5 million and Employers Liability
      Insurance of 10 million must be provided.
      
      The contractor must hold or employ persons with valid HSE asbestos license
      to be able to remove notifiable asbestos (if any).

column52: 2017/S 120-242653 Dementia Care Safe Beds
column53:
Safe Beds are an alternative admission to an acute hospital for people with a superimposed delirium on dementia.
Walsall CCG intends to operate a twelve month pilot with a suitably experienced local nursing home provider (The Lakes) with capacity for the provision of up to six Safe Beds @ a rate of 1,500 per bed per week. This will be with a view to proving concept and within 6 months of operating the pilot the CCG will review the outcomes and if successful in the following six months undertake a procurement for the service with a view to awarding a contract for three years, with an option to extend by a further two.
The successful operator will be in, or in close proximity to, Walsall. 
Providers must operate in a dementia friendly environment with six beds away from existing residents and must also be experienced and currently providing care to people with dementia and behaviour that challenges. Staff skills should be in both dementia and physical health care. 
When tendering the commissioner will assess potential providers through a combination of evaluating tender responses, presentations and site visits to assess the relevance of the provider's experience, the extent of the experience, the suitability of the existing environment, the capability of staff and management arrangements and the track record of outcomes. These will be assessed in equal measure. 
Both the pilot and the tendered service will be provided in accordance with the terms of the 2017-18 NHS Standard Contract (or the latest iteration).
A call for competition will be issued as part of the procurement process.

column23: Getting the most from developmental reviews of leadership and governance using the well-led framework in the NHS
column36: Early engagement notice on Contracts Finder
column52: Getting the most from developmental reviews of leadership and governance using the well-led framework in the NHS
column53:
NHS Improvement wishes to seek views from potential suppliers about how we can maximise the benefit from developmental reviews using the well-led framework, which will be commissioned by NHS provider trusts.

BACKGROUND
In-depth, regular, and independent reviews of leadership and governance are good practice across all industries. Rather than solely assessing the current position of providers in the NHS against the well-led framework, these reviews should identify the areas of leadership and governance of organisations that would benefit from further targeted development work to secure and sustain future improvement.                  

Independent and objective assessment as part of these reviews is vital to safeguard against the optimism bias and group think to which even the best organisations may be susceptible. Our guidance therefore recommends that trusts commission an external supplier to coordinate and facilitate the reviews every 3 - 5 years.  Please see the framework guidance for more details: 
LINK https://improvement.nhs.uk/resources/well-led-framework/                                                     

Reviews are likely to take the form of commissioning consultancy firms with expertise across the eight domains of the new well-led framework, published in June 2017.  Assuming an even spread of reviews across the suggested period, there may be c.50 reviews commissioned by individual trusts per year.  

INVITATION TO CONTRIBUTE                                                   
As part of increasing the value derived from these reviews, and enhancing the knowledge sharing between providers across the NHS, we are establishing a system of peer review to support trusts in their development and preparing new guidance to promote better practice in commissioning suppliers. 

We would like to explore the questions that arise from this approach to developmental well-led reviews with a range of potential suppliers.  As a supplier, this would give you the opportunity to consider your offering to providers in the NHS in the future, consistent with the new well-led framework and the approach to peer review.

ENGAGEMENT EVENT: 
We are holding a market engagement event to discuss the questions attached to this notice. This will take place in the afternoon on WEDNESDAY 12 JULY 2017 in London. A dial in facility will be available, but in person attendance would be preferred. 

If you would like to attend, please email the names of your delegates (maximum 2 per organisation) to v.partridge@nhs.net BY 5pm on THURSDAY 6 JULY 2017; further details of the meeting will be sent to those who respond by this date.              

If you are not able to attend the meeting, you are welcome to provide written feedback to v.partridge@nhs.net by on 5pm 12 July 2017.

Additional information: NHS Improvement wishes to seek views from suppliers about how we can make sure their engagement enables maximum benefit to be derived from developmental reviews.  


The two key areas for comment are in relation to:
	Developing new guidance that promotes better practice in commissioning suppliers to deliver effective developmental well-led reviews
	Embedding peer review as part of the external teams to enable the sharing of experience more widely in the NHS Trust sector.

QUESTIONS TO BE CONSIDERED AT EVENT
In particular, we would like to explore the following questions regarding developmental well-led reviews:
	What can providers in the NHS do to improve commissioning of reviews leading to improved products that will enhance supplier take-up as well as leading to lasting improvement in the NHS provider sector?  

	What issues within specifications make it easier for suppliers to deliver an appropriate service; what has been less helpful? 

	What is your appetite for working with peer reviewers from the NHS? 

	How would you need to adapt your approach to make use of peer input? 

	What needs to be considered before peer reviewers can be engaged, e.g. regarding the management of liabilities? 

	In what ways could we harness the learning from suppliers undertaking multiple reviews?

column52: Electronic Archive Management System
column53:
Herefordshire Archive Service collects, preserves and makes available for research the archives produced by a wide range of individuals and organisations in Herefordshire and the diocese of Hereford. These functions incorporate several interconnected activities:

	Accessioning - the receipt and logging of archives transferred to Herefordshire Archive and Records Centre (HARC)
	Cataloguing - describing archives so that they can be accessed
	Preservation/ conservation - archival storage, packaging and repair of documents

Currently, these processes are carried out by means of disparate paper based systems and general electronic applications. Herefordshire Council is looking to introduce an externally hosted archive management system to bring all these processes together.
